> Bulgur wheat isn't the most frequent guest at the dinner table, so we've
> invited it to join the party for this recipe! High in fibre and protein and
> low on the glycaemic index, it's a great source of nutrition and, more
> importantly, it tastes great. Bulgur wheat is eaten a lot in the Middle East
> and South Asia where people have been enjoying it for thousands of years.
> We've teamed it up with a fantastic sweet and sour pork, for a recipe which
> is as delicious as it is easy.

Bring the @water{600%ml} to the boil in a #pot{} with the @vegetable stock pot{1}. Pour in the @bulgur wheat{300%g}, place a #lid{} on the pot and rest off the heat for ~{25%minutes}, or until the water has completely soaked into the wheat.

Meanwhile, peel and chop the @garlic clove{3}(peeled and chopped). Remove the core from the @red pepper{1}(chopped into bite-sized chunks) and @yellow pepper{1}(chopped into bite-sized chunks). Thinly slice the @spring onion{3}(thinly sliced), separating the white and green parts.

Cut the @pork medallion{4} into bite-sized cubes and season with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Sprinkle the @cornflour{2%tbsp} onto a #plate{} and coat your pork thoroughly on all sides.

Turn your hob to high and heat a splash of @oil{} in a #frying pan{}. Line a large plate with #kitchen paper{}. When the pan is hot, add half your pork and fry until brown (about ~{4%minutes}). Transfer your pork to the lined plate to drain the oil, then fry the remainder and add to the plate too.

In a #small bowl{}, mix the @Chinese rice vinegar{2%tbsp} with a sprinkle of @?sugar{pinch}. Stir until your sugar has dissolved then set aside.

Rinse the #frying pan{} used for your pork then put on medium-high heat. Add a splash of @oil{} and cook your garlic and your whites of your spring onion for ~{1%minute}. Add your pepper chunks and cook for ~{4%minutes}. Add the @kecap manis{4%tbsp} and your vinegar mixture and bring to a simmer.

Return your pork to the pan and stir thoroughly. Continue cooking for ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper, if needed.

Serve your pork with your bulgur wheat on the side. Sprinkle with your remaining spring onion and enjoy!